solution: ```class MedianFinder:
    import heapq
    def __init__(self):
        self.lo = []   # max-heap (negated values)
        self.hi = []   # min-heap

    def addNum(self, num: int) -> None:
        heapq.heappush(self.lo, -num)
        if self.lo and self.hi and (-self.lo[0] > self.hi[0]):
            val = -heapq.heappop(self.lo)
            heapq.heappush(self.hi, val)
        if len(self.lo) > len(self.hi) + 1:
            val = -heapq.heappop(self.lo)
            heapq.heappush(self.hi, val)
        if len(self.hi) > len(self.lo):
            val = heapq.heappop(self.hi)
            heapq.heappush(self.lo, -val)

    def findMedian(self) -> float:
        if len(self.lo) > len(self.hi):
            return float(-self.lo[0])
        return (-self.lo[0] + self.hi[0]) / 2.0
```
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(log N) addNum, O(1) findMedian
space complexity: O(N)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: Uses two heaps to maintain the lower and upper halves of the data stream. The max-heap (lo) and min-heap (hi) are balanced so their tops give the median in constant time. Each insertion triggers at most three heap operations, each O(log N).

